Maldon District Council is seeking Tender submissions for the main Waste and Recycling Collection services to be delivered over a five-day weekly cycle (Monday to Friday).
The Contract Commencement date for this Contract is 1st February 2016. On this date the Contractor shall operate the current range of services operated by the Council and as described in more detail in the Specification:
  Household Residual Waste on a weekly basis in sacks;
  Mixed Dry Recyclables – newspaper, paper, card and telephone directories on a weekly basis from 55 litre boxes (apart from approximately 900 properties which present these materials in disposable sacks);
  Mixed Dry Recyclables – plastic packaging, food tins, drinks cans, foil and aerosols on a weekly basis from 55 litre box bags (apart from approximately 900 properties which present these materials in disposable sacks);
  Mixed Glass (bottles and jars) on a weekly basis from 55 litre boxes (apart from approximately 900 properties which present these materials in disposable sacks);
  Food Waste on a weekly basis from 23 litre kerbside caddies (kitchen caddies also provided);
  Garden Waste on a weekly basis from 240 litre wheeled bins (subscription service) from March to November reducing to fortnightly collections for the winter months December to February.  A small number of properties present Garden Waste in disposable sacks which require splitting;
  Provision of a Bulky Waste Service including the collection of WEEE (fridge/freezers/CRTs/Large domestic appliances) for Re-Use or Recycling; and
  The servicing of 33 Bring Sites within the Maldon District Council area.

From the 6th June 2016 the Contractor shall commence New Services which will provide an enhanced Waste and Recycling service:
  Household Residual Waste on a fortnightly basis from 180 litre wheeled bins other than those on the Small/Larger Container List or the Exemption List;
  Mixed Dry Recyclables (excluding glass) on a fortnightly basis in clear sacks. This service includes as a minimum cardboard & paper, drink/food and aerosol cans, plastics (rigid food containers, bottles including lid), aluminium foil and foil containers, beverage drinks cartons;
  Mixed Glass on a fortnightly basis from 55 litre boxes, for recycling as a separate stream from the Mixed Dry Recyclables;
  Food Waste on a weekly basis from 23 litre kerbside caddies;
  Garden Waste (subscription service) on a weekly basis from 240 litre wheeled bins reducing to fortnightly in the winter months of December to February;
  Provision of a Bulky Waste Service including the collection of WEEE (fridge/freezers/CRTs/Large domestic appliances) for Re-Use or Recycling; and
  The servicing of 33 Bring Sites within the Maldon District Council area.

Please email wasteprocurement@maldon.gov.uk to express an interest and to guarantee receiving all clarification information.

Lincolnshire County Council are looking for a supplier to provide site staff and management for a Household Waste Recycling Centre in Boston, Lincolnshire. 
The successful supplier shall be responsible for;
the day to day management and staffing of the HWRC;
the acceptance and sorting of household waste deposited by customers;
operating plant on site;
site cleanliness and landscaping;
the upkeep of buildings;
site security (excluding CCTV);
health and safety and 
compliance with all relevant legislation.

Nottingham City Council invited tenders from suitably experienced and qualified entities for the provision of a number of Legionella Services within their asset portfolio mainly located within the City of Nottingham and Newstead Abbey and Wollaton Park. The appointed contractor will supply services for the delivery of Legionella Control package consisting of:

Part 1: A regular programme of work consisting of:

(i) planned maintenance for chlorine dioxide units;

(ii) provision of Legionella risk assessment for large sites;

(iii) taking water samples from leisure centre pools.

Part 2: reactive and remedial works, (24/7 and 365 days per year) as per section 4) for chlorine dioxide units and water sampling associated works.

Kent County Council (KCC) is looking for an organisation that can provide a site for, and manage and operate a new Household Waste Recycling Centre (HWRC) in the Tonbridge &amp; Malling area on behalf of KCC, including waste haulage services. Bidders will also be given the option to deliver waste disposal services on behalf of KCC relating to specific waste materials collected at the HWRC. 
The new HWRC must be located within the administrative area of Kent and within or close to the primary search area shown on the map below, defined as &#039;to the west of the Maidstone Town Centre and to the north of the town of West Malling but contained within the proximity or locality of the M20/A20 corridor&#039;. The HWRC must be easily accessible from the primary road network to ensure the site operates efficiently with minimal impact upon the surrounding area. 
The new HWRC must be sited on suitable land (planning and environmental permitting wise) between 1 and 5 hectares in size. The timescales for this project are tight and therefore to achieve delivery within this timescale, it is desirable for the site to either have an existing waste or industrial use. 
The site must be of a modern design such that it can comply with all current Environment Agency Environmental Permitting requirements and have a long enough access/entrance way within the site as to not cause any excessive queuing on the highway.
The HWRC must be able to accept the full list of waste streams accepted at KCC HWRCs, as set out below:
•	Green waste;
•	Residual;
•	Bulky;
•	Metal;
•	Wood;
•	Paper and Card;
•	WEEE segregated into Small WEEE/ LDA&#039;s,/Cooling/Displays and Lamps;
•	Textiles;
•	Glass;
•	Tyres;
•	Engine Oil and Engine oil containers;
•	Cooking Oil;
•	Lead Acid Batteries;
•	Dry Cell Batteries;
•	Asbestos;
•	Plasterboard;
•	Soil;
•	Rubble and Hardcore;
•	Gas Bottle and Aerosols;
•	Chemicals;
•	Toner Cartridges; and
•	Additional capacity required to take account of future additional waste streams/enforced segregation/overflow.
In addition, KCC wish to have a re-use shop as part of the HWRC facility.
KCC will be looking for a sustainable facility that makes best use of energy efficient design features, such as solar panels, rainwater harvesting and sustainable drainage systems. 
The design of the site should follow the waste hierarchy with reuse first, followed by recycling bays and lastly residual to encourage customers to consider how they dispose of their waste.
The HWRC shall be open to the public seven days a week in line with the rest of KCC&#039;s network of sites.
•	Monday to Saturday: 8am - 4:30pm
•	Sunday and bank holidays: 9am - 4pm
•	Closed: Christmas Day, Boxing Day and New Year&#039;s Day.
There may be a requirement to extend operating hours during the summer months based on demand.
